The story is good. The book itself has 12 different endings. Its in your best interest to specialize in intimidation, persuasion, or perception. The game pacing is somewhat fast, moving from scene to scene of someones life, it is not as full of dialogue or description as I would like it to be. The plot moves forward in a definitive way. Its definitely a good read with lots of replayability.

Overall, the story wasn't bad, but definitely not up to par with other COG/Hosted Games. I really dislike this authors writing style. Instead of writing an actual story, they just say "I did this" "This thing happened" "Then I did this". It's pretty lazy honestly. If you're looking for a well written and entertaining COG/Hosted Game, play Samurai of Hyuga, Versus or Zombie Exodus. Much better writing, in my opinion.

Life of a Mobster plays out practically every little mob fantasy you can imagine. And that's not a bad thing, tightly paced, competently written, and utterly ruthless in handling choice and consequences. The game is a splendid dive for anyone after a wild ride with the classic style of organised crime. With a little more length, and perhaps a little more flexibility over stat restrictions, which can often lock down a very good story. This could be have been a stellar CoG, but it's still a gripping one.
I would love more of this type of setting. Even if its not about mobsters, the way you choreographed this one was flawless, loved it.

The one thing I can say about this game, is it keeps you replaying to get a different outcome.  Over all its the same story with few deviations, but it changes just enough to keep you engaged and coming back for more.  I still haven't mastered every ending yet, and I've played through at least twelve times now.  Great game for its price.

I was impressed my first play through, but that was it. As you progress through the game, you are given choices on almost every screen where you can choose how to deal with your situation, which increases your stats. However, the game is so heavily stats-based that if you want a successful ending you have to make the same choices in order to increase a certain stat, making the game linear and boring as your choices dwindle. Not much replayability, as there are no real changes you can make. Solid OK.
